A picture to understand: Bitcoin's legal status around the world
In addition to the price correction naturally triggered by speculative attributes, the collapse of this round of digital currency is also related to the "enemy" - regulatory risk.
From the visual map, the attitude of Eastern countries towards Bitcoin is more conservative than that of the West, and the countries that account for the majority of the world are still waiting for the legitimacy of digital currency, which represents the "black swan risk" is still very large.
*This article is from Wall Street News (WeChat ID: wallstreetcn), editor Wang Mu. For more information, please visit wallstreet.com, or download the Wall Street News app.*
With the regulatory storm in major bitcoin markets such as China, South Korea and the European Union, and the global digital currency led by Bitcoin has been bloody this week, and the price of Bitcoin fell below the psychological integer bit of $10,000 on Tuesday, and the largest one-day decline in three years.
In addition to the price correction naturally triggered by speculative attributes, the collapse of this round of digital currency is also related to the "enemy" - regulatory risk.
At this important juncture, the visual big data website HowMuch.net has produced an atlas showing the legitimacy and degree of regulation of Bitcoin in countries around the world.
As shown in the figure below, green represents the legal market for Bitcoin; orange represents the neutral market, although it has not yet publicly legalized Bitcoin status, but there is no major restriction on use; pale pink represents the restricted market, that is, the local government tries to use the digital currency through red line policy or regulation; dark pink represents the country that is defined as Bitcoin illegal; gray is the country that has not yet commented.
(Photo by HowMuch.Net visualization team on January 15th.)
The article pointed out that from the distribution of green blocks in the figure, it can be seen that the attitude of Eastern countries to Bitcoin in the traditional sense is more conservative than that of the West.
Russia is currently the largest country that defines Bitcoin as illegal, China is one of the largest restricted markets for Bitcoin, and India is one of the largest countries that has not yet issued relevant policies for Bitcoin.
North America and Western Europe are the regions with the highest acceptance of Bitcoin, where the distribution of green blocks is more concentrated.
The views of countries in the Middle East and Latin America on Bitcoin are clearly divided, and the color block distribution in these regions is more mixed.
Among them, Iraq, Iran, Turkey, Brazil are the legal bitcoin market, Afghanistan, Pakistan, Saudi Arabia, Egypt, Bolivia and other countries have some degree of restrictions on their trading and use, more Latin American countries have not yet voiced their views on Bitcoin.
According to the above data, 99 of the 246 countries in the world are excluded (or 40%) without restrictions on the trading and use of Bitcoin, that is, green and orange.
Seven countries (or 3%) are restricted markets (light pink), 10 (or 4%) define Bitcoin as illegal (dark pink), and 130 countries (or 53%) do not yet have more information about digital currencies (grey).
This shows that the countries that account for the majority of the world (53%, more than half) are still waiting to see the legitimacy of the digital currency led by Bitcoin in China, and also represents that the “black swan risk” of Bitcoin is still very large, because some of these countries may eventually make legislative decisions to restrict the digital currency.
The article believes that global regulators do not fully understand the emerging category of digital currency, which may be the main reason why most countries have not yet made a statement.
Although Bitcoin’s “beverage” has grown exponentially since last year, it does not mean that all countries are interested, and some countries may be worried that local fiat currencies will be threatened as a result, or more worried about the digital currency being used by criminal organizations.
Wall Street has written a detailed summary of the international regulatory news against bitcoin since last week, including China’s crackdown on centralized online platforms and mobile apps for over-the-counter exchanges, South Korea is still considering closing digital currency exchanges, and the European Union’s belief that bitcoin has not been widely accepted and warned investors about the risk of “losing money.”
Read the editor-in-chief's "Reading News | 2018: The world's central mother opened the first year of digital currency?" once mentioned that from any point of view of supervision, acceptance/criticism and adoption, 2018 will become the first year of digital currency for global central banks.
The criticism of bitcoin’s legitimacy by big powers such as Russia is also to make way for the official issuance of digital currency.
