Blocking critics on Facebook: If you can't stand the blame of voters, don't run for public office
Our father-in-law understands the bad media style.
Americans loved Washington, but soon after, the major newspapers began to lash out at everything he had, from domestic policy to political principles.
He was irritated by these criticisms, no doubt.
But he did not silence these critics.
As early as 1783, Washington said, “Freedom of speech is denied—we will be slaughtered in silence and ignorance like lambs.”
It reminds me of Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who needs to learn from Washington.
Hogan’s staff blocked and removed the posts of at least 450 people because they posted their views on his Facebook page.
The American Civil Liberties Union filed a lawsuit against him earlier this week.
The governor’s staff thought the lawsuit was sloppy, with online reports rife with their strong resistance: “Who cares?”
A lot of people say, "It's just Facebook."
But that is important.
This is especially important because it is the case with people like Hogan.
He is a Republican governor in a predominantly Democratic state, and he is also surprisingly popular.
Of the 50 governors in the country, he received the second highest praise.
Hogan is not a reactionary impetuous man.
He was in control of Maryland and strictly adhered to the rules.
He is also very good at using Facebook as the main way to connect with voters, jokingly showing his baldness after chemotherapy on the homepage for the first time.
So blocking people who come to the governor's homepage for comment is completely unnecessary and ultimately dangerous. This home page is a public forum, the official management platform advertised by the public tax-provided staff.
In an interview with The Washington Post, Hogan’s spokeswoman, Amelia Shas, defended the governor’s actions, saying she believed blocking their comments was nothing more than a attempt to restrain them.
But they have too hastily described it as a flood of beasts or cynics sweeping the web.
The Washington Post spoke face-to-face with people blocked by Hogan.
They are just ordinary people talking to their chosen leaders: they are teachers, small business owners, and pastors, not a flood of beasts.
They have expressed their depth, respect, and indiminency.
The pastor quoted the Bible in his post, calling on Hogan to remember his Catholic faith.
Raxemi Salma Lamani, a barrister in Bowie, Maryland, was not cynical, but she asked questions about hate crimes.
She wrote in a news story commentary section of The Washington Post, “I am politely commenting that I am disappointed that he did not respond to hate crimes and other recent news events.”
I also don’t like a bunch of people commenting on the same topic, because they are directly ignored by some people who think they are so-called herd mentality, rather than treating them as a group of worried citizens.”
What the governor’s staff called “intensive spam bombardment” may have been “insisted claims” to others.
The Facebook era made it easy to change a message, simply blocking one critic or removing one negative comment.
And it’s far cleaner than it used to be, and to do the same thing in the past, it would have required sending staff out to collect and burn critical newspapers or arrest or silence protesters.
But that’s really what’s happening now, but on a digital level.
Hogan is not the first public official to be blamed for suing others on Facebook and other social media.
President Trump is being sued by Twitter users for blocking them on Twitter.
Last week saw a landmark ruling in Virginia on such issues.
According to District Judge James C. Catsari of Alexandria, the chairman of the Lawden County Oversight Committee’s blocking of voters from her Facebook page violates the First Amendment.
Kentucky Governor Matt Bevin (R) is also patronized by the American Civil Liberties Union for his use of Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be so difficult.
In the Washington era, affordable postage and the Internet had similar influence.
The number of newspapers quadrupled between 1776 and 1800, and anonymous letters were written as critical of his leadership.
And even then, Washington had an anonymous flood of beasts against him.
People used pseudonyms such as Yurikra, Valerius, Belisarius, and Poius to write harshly to criticize Washington's decision-making.
According to historical documents collected by the George Washington newspaper online project, his office was inundated with petitions criticizing his attitude to the Treaty of Friendship, Commerce and Navigation between His Majesty the King of England and the United States of America.
But he didn’t silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and speech are the foundation of this country.
Real leaders need to accept this.
