Poverty and death in Indonesia
Baddine Dejie doesn’t use the stove when she cooks.
She rarely even uses pots.
Her wooden house is located in Enarotali, the capital of Panai County in Indonesia’s Papua province, and the housewife usually puts just a sweet potato — which locals call “nota” — directly into the fire.
Half an hour later, the charred sweet potato was taken out by a pair of unwashed hands and eaten.
Dai Jie sat on the mud—she had no furniture, and it was where she did her daily household chores, such as washing clothes, and the water for washing clothes was very turbid, all from the nearby marshes.
There was a bucket in a room without a roof, which was the outdoor toilet.
She was the youngest of her husband’s four wives, so she was not assigned to the field to take care of her.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working until the party was very dangerous: most of the men in the village did not have a job, and many were drunk, plus there were many soldiers here.
She said, "No one dares to walk around the village after 5 p.m."
It is a rare glimpse of everyday life in the Papuan Highlands, once a Dutch colony that was incorporated into Indonesia after a referendum in 1969, but the referendum was also controversial when only 1,026 elders were forced to vote by show of hands in front of the army that occupied the area.
The current campaign to demand independence and opposition to Dutch rule soon took aim at the Jakarta government, which imposed heavy-handed rule on the region and isolated foreign journalists and activists.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, while Papua New Guinea controlled the eastern part of the island independently.
Ana Rotali is remote and uninhabited; to get here, you need to take a 90-minute flight from the provincial capital, Chaiapura, to Napierre, and then rent a car for 5 hours, all the way to the stomach.
There is no public transportation here.
In this town of about 19,000 people, the wooden house is surrounded by bamboo fences, and the folded tin roof is a tawny cover made of rust.
Few Indonesians came, let alone journalists, and almost no foreigners.
Before the arrival of the Christian evangelists, the Mee Pago Papuans believed in a god called Uga Tamee.
There are other changes here too.
Dai Jie said, "We can't wear these clothes." She was referring to her brightly colored hand-knitted turban, dark shirt and bright half-dress.
"We used to cover our bodies with only leaves."
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, where 28% of the population lives below the poverty line and is the region with the highest infant mortality rate and the lowest literacy rate.
It is also the Golden Continent of Indonesia.
Panai County is located in the highlands, about the same size as New Jersey, and has 153,000 people. The world's largest and most profitable gold mine, Grassberg, is located just 60 miles from the Phoenix-based Felipe McMurran Copper and Gold Company.
In 2015 alone, Felipe mined about $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper mines.
In addition, Papua is rich in timber resources, with an estimated value of $78 billion.
However, these abundant resources are also the source of the Papuan tragedy, and Indonesia's powerful military forces have been able to suppress them.
A 2005 New York Times investigation found that Philip paid nearly $20 million to local military personnel and troops between 1998 and 2004, and an official alone was as high as $150,000.
The Papuans’ growing demands for independence threatened the gold owner and were brutally treated.
Since 1969, more than half a million Papuans have been killed and thousands raped, tortured and detained by Indonesian forces, according to activists.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, mass killings in the Papua tribal highlands of the 1970s have escalated into genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters.
A 2016 report by the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Brisbane, We Will Lose Everything, included evidence of the previous year’s manifests, such as extrajudicial killings, torture – another report says rape and electricity are particularly prevalent – and the brutal crackdown on peaceful demonstrations.
Andreas Halsono, an Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch, said, “Violence is taking place on a daily basis, making it difficult to calculate the number of victims.”
Papua’s resources attracted large numbers of immigrants outside of Indonesia, and the oppression began.
Eighty-three percent of the province's 3.5 million people are Christian, but the demographics of Muslim economic immigrants have changed since the densely populated islands of Java, Kalimantan, Sumatra, and Sulawesi.
The Javanese food stand sells a mixture of fried chicken and vegetables, with peanut butter.
The locals are struggling.
Apos You, a 24-year-old local, moved to Chayapura, the provincial capital, to find work, explaining that “those immigrants started selling chicken and vegetables in traditional markets at lower prices than local Papuans.”
This caused the local Papuans, the Papuan women (mama-mama) – to lose their market.”
Indonesian President Joko Widodo (often referred to as Jokowi) vowed at his 2014 election campaign to address Papuan inequality and abuse of power.
The former carpenter’s road to Jakarta’s presidential palace was supported by 27 of all 29 districts – including Panai.
But nothing has changed in Papua, and today, the locals feel betrayed.
“We have broken our hearts and we voted for Jokowi in 2014 in the hope that he will fulfill our wish and restore fairness.”
In fact, just two months after Jokowi took office in October, Panai suffered his worst nightmare.
On December 7, 2014, 11 children in Ana Rotali were singing a Christmas carol in front of a bonfire outside, and two Indonesian soldiers rushed over on a motorcycle.
The frightened children told them they should turn on the headlights.
According to local pastor Yahweh Tebay, one of the soldiers was dissatisfied with their tone and returned with four soldiers.
The victims and witnesses said the drunken soldiers chased the children with their guns.
Then one of the soldiers fired a gun at the children.
Sixteen-year-old Julianus Yemme was unconscious after being badly beaten.
A few hours later, a blaze ignited in the building of the nearby government agency Election Commission, and the incident escalated the next day.
About 1,000 young Papuan men, women and children gathered at a football stadium in front of the local police station and the military command center to demand justice.
With ritualistic bows, they danced the waita dance of the Babuya Mee Pago tribe—running around in circles and mimicking birdsong.
Some protesters began throwing stones at regular military checkpoints.
According to an official document seen by Time magazine, as the mood continued to intensify, the soldiers received an order via internal radio: "If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them immediately." But the document was not released to local media.
Jeremias Kayamu, 56, the head of the Kego Koto neighbourhood of Ana Rotali, felt that there was imminent danger, called for calm and begged them to go home.
No one was in the mood to listen to him.
He stood on the porch of his brightly colored wooden house and told Time magazine, "When I turned around, my left wrist was suddenly shot."
Kayami still did not know who fired the gun, but he said the bullets came from among the assembled soldiers.
He added, "It was crowded, they fired a lot of shots."
According to the cousins of Orfyus Juul, he witnessed the shooting and saw Orfyus Juul shot three times.
Yuhanes sadly told Time magazine, “I ran over to check if his body was him,
I found out he was dead... I kissed him."
Papua police chief inspector Yuji Mend told reporters that his subordinates were only "protecting" the police station because the police station was attacked.
In 2015, Papua police spokesman, Police Chief Puzio Suristior, said: “When someone threatens to kill us, we have to defend ourselves.
It's a matter of life and death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more injured.
The next day news of the killing only spread slowly in Jakarta.
Three weeks later, Jokowi gave a speech in Jayapura, expressing deep sympathy for the families of the victims and vowing to address the abuses left over from Papua’s history.
He said, “I hope this case will be resolved as soon as possible, so that this will not happen again in the future.”
In October 2016, Security Minister Wilando said he wanted to set up a non-judicial mechanism to address the historical legacy of human rights violations.
But the excuse of disbar was almost immediately invoked.
He said, “Most of the violations happened a long time ago.
Some were in the 1990s and early 2000s.
The point is that we are committed to addressing these violations, but it still requires a process.”
Then in Jakarta on June 5, Wilando, in a conversation with Time magazine, said he had no plans to establish a complaint mechanism in Papua.
On the contrary, he said, “Everything will be settled in accordance with the law”.
The United Nations has filed a complaint against Wilando for “crimes against human rights” over more than 1,000 deaths in a bloodied independence vote in East Timor in 1999, but said 11 human rights violations in Papua have been resolved, including the Panai incident.
The families of the victims of the Panai incident scoffed at these words.
“I’ve had four interviews in the last three years, but things haven’t gone well,” Juhanes said.
Years later, he said, "I'm tired."
He is still living in fear.
He said, “I’m scared.
I'm afraid of being arrested by the military, I'm afraid of being shot."
His brother Yukabus also believed that the people of Panai were afraid to talk about the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after helping to bury the four victims.
He said, "After the body was buried, the military came to me."
The shooting did not stop.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot villagers in De Yai County, Panai neighboring county.
A construction company manager refused to help transport a comatose man to the hospital, where clashes ensued, one person was killed and another 17 injured, including children.
Rajanus Dow, a 24-year-old man who was fishing in the nearby river, drowned on his way to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the company's on-site office.
Police said villagers threw stones at police, so officers fired warning shots.
But the riot mobile unit (Indonesian paramilitary police) began shooting at the crowd, and one person was killed.
Domingu Badi, 29, told Time magazine, “We were all panicked and now we’re afraid they’re going to get revenge.” He was living near the hospital and witnessed the wounded being rushed to the hospital.
"I hid at home for two days."
The Deyai parliament has called for the police involved to be brought to justice and the withdrawal of riot mobile forces from the area.
Panai has always been a rightful place for the Indonesian government.
The lack of effective development has fostered the discontent of the people of Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal, scattered in the lush central highlands of Panai.
Many have joined the Free Papua Movement (OPM), a rebel group that claims to protect the rights of the Papuans through scattered attacks and raids to kidnap Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the top leaders of the Free Papuan Movement were born in Panai, including Tadius Yug and Daniel Yodas Kogoya.
As a result, thousands of Panais have been arrested and deliberately detained in recent years under the guise of “maintaining national sovereignty” by the military.
Some have not appeared again.
In the eyes of the Papuans, Panai is a “place of forgotten tragedy.”
Poverty breeds discontent.
Ana Rotali sells so little rice that the locals simply can’t afford.
Bread is out of reach.
Here the people grow everything they can eat: mainly sweet potatoes and some fruits and leaves of vegetables.
Farming is a woman’s job, and every woman can take care of four or five pieces of sweet potato land.
They usually keep most of the harvest for writers, and the rest is sold on the local market.
Ten sweet potatoes are worth only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, economic inequality has been drawn up among local Papuans and new immigrants, and the number of these migrants has increased significantly since the opening of the new route to Napierre Airport.
The small number of jobs available often falls into the hands of better educated and wealthier immigrants.
Papuans have little capital or the necessary skills to run competitive companies.
John Goby, president of the Parnian Tribal Council, said that “young people do not want to stay in this village ... because there is no work and no money”.
Papua is isolated.
Restrictions on international media coverage remain tight.
Earlier this year, French journalists Frank Escudi and Basel Longchamp were expelled from Papua because they “do not cooperate with the relevant agencies,” even though they have received rare authorizations for filming.
According to Felim Kane, deputy Asia director at Human Rights Watch, Jokowi’s election pledge to lift reporting restrictions to promote transparency and development has not been fulfilled.
“If foreign journalists try to cover the most popular provinces in Indonesia, Papua and West Papua, the easternmost provinces, they are at new risk: denial of visas and blacklisting,” he said in a statement.
The absence of media scrutiny means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is largely confined to Papua’s neighbors.
In March, six Pacific nations — Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands, and the Solomon Islands — asked the U.N. Human Rights Council to investigate “all kinds of widespread human rights violations,” including the Panai shooting.
These countries have also supported the Free Papua Movement .
The spokesman for the Indonesian Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Almanata Nasir, was concerned about the allegations against the group, telling reporters in Jakarta that “Indonesia is still in its democratic institutions and the media is free, so the evidence of human rights violations is difficult to conceal.”
Locals want more foreign governments to pay attention.
On May 4, when the Dutch ambassador for human rights, Keswan Barr, led a delegation of officials to Jayapura, the local people broke their silence and begged for “we want freedom.” He also attended the meeting, but requested anonymity.
Indonesia will hold its next presidential election in 2019, but Papuans say they are unlikely to vote in Jokowi again.
Goby, the chairman of the tribal council, said: “Zokowi’s intentions were good, but he was surrounded by people involved in the Panai shooting.”
He wanted Jokowi to know that the people of Panai not only lived under the threat of a greedy army, but that there was nothing but that the region was little educated and public health care services were scarce.
Gobai said the Panai people, like other Papuans, believed that the vote they had voted for Jokowi was a debt he had to pay.
He said, "They don't need money, they need justice."
Even under threat and intimidation, the families of the victims of the Panai shooting made their last symbolic revolt: the body of a victim buried opposite the military police post.
They know that justice may never come, but at least they won’t let the culprits forget their crimes.
Yukabus said, “My family was killed.
What else can we do?”
