EPA Administrator Pruitt changes his mind about Obama-era emissions cuts
A day after being sued by 15 states, Environmental Protection Agency Administrator Scott Pruitt reversed his earlier decision to delay implementing Obama-era regulations to reduce emissions of smog pollutants.
Pruitt proposed the change because the Environmental Protection Agency was able to respond more quickly to the needs of environmental regulatory state agencies than previous governments.
He made no mention of the legal challenge brought by the federal appeals court against his former post.
The focus of the dispute is setting a Oct. 1 deadline for states to begin meeting the 2015 ground-level ozone standard.
In June, Pruitt announced that he would delay his compliance by a year to give the Environmental Protection Agency more time to study the plan and avoid “interference with local decision-making or hindering economic growth.”
Prior to his appointment by President Donald Trump, Pruitt was Oklahoma’s attorney general, a longtime opposition to the rigor of environmental regulations.
Since arriving in Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly turned to blocking or postponing regulations that the chemical and fossil fuel industries oppose.
Wednesday’s sudden reversal is the latest legal hurdle on Pruitt’s regulatory back-to-extension agenda.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the head of the Environmental Protection Agency overstepped his authority in an attempt to delay the implementation of the Obama administration’s rules requiring oil and gas companies to monitor and reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released Wednesday night, Pruitt offered a U-turn on his approach to ozone standards, saying he wanted to strengthen the Environmental Protection Agency’s commitment to work with states to adopt complex procedures to meet new standards.
Pruitt said that “under the previous administration, the EPA usually did not meet the deadline, then waited for radical groups and others to sue, and then agreed to set a timetable for the designation by agreement.” He initiated more than a dozen prosecutions against the Environmental Protection Agency in his previous work.
“We don’t believe in regulation through litigation, and we take deadlines seriously.
We also take the regulations and the authorities seriously.”
Still, the EPA statement said Pruitt may again use his “extended authorization and all other legally available authorizations” to ensure that the regulations comply with “good policy and the best information available.”
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a broad rewrite of the ozone layer ordinance.
The House bill, approved last month, aims to delay the 2015 rule by at least eight years.
The measure has not yet been voted on in the Senate.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman led a coalition of states to sue the EPA this week, saying it intends to maintain legal pressure.
“The EPA’s inversion — after we filed a lawsuit — is a significant victory for the health and safety of 6.7 million New Yorkers, with communities of more than 115 million Americans directly affected by smog emissions,” Schneiderman said.
California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont and Washington, and the District of Columbia all joined New York State in the case.
Ground-level ozone is formed by common pollutants emitted by automobiles, power plants, refineries, chemical plants and other sources that react under sunlight in the atmosphere.
The resulting smog can cause serious breathing problems for sensitive people and cause thousands of premature deaths each year.
Of course, public health advocates and environmentalists cheered Pruitt’s surprising transformation.
Lori Ann Bird of the Centre for Biological Diversity said: “It is disturbing that this common-sense measure is under intense pressure from the head of the department that protects the air we need to breathe.”
“We must fight to the end with the Trump administration’s ideological movement to cater to polluters and special interests.”
