A 1948 Ford Mercury car runs through a crowd of onlookers in the small town of Monroe, Georgia, toward the tiny Moor Beach Bridge.
The car was carrying four black passengers and a white driver, and before the car arrived at the bridge, a group of white people with guns stepped forward and blocked the way forward.
The head of this gang of thugs — a middle-aged man in a pinstriped suit — took a deep sip of a cigar and glanced into the windshield.
Passengers in the car are full of fear.
"We want - Roger!" cried the man.
“Get him out of the car!”
A young black man was dragged down from the front passenger seat with screams piercing silence.
Fortunately, this terrible scene on July 22 was just a repeat.
But when “Roger” put a noose around his neck, almost all the spectators onlookers gave a real gasp.
Since 2005, civil rights activists have returned to Moore Beach Bridge to recreate the scene of two black couples — Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and Mere Dosi — who were lynched by the Three Klux Klan parties in 1946.
No one has ever been charged with murder.
“While we know who they are, and despite what we’ve seen in the community, it’s incredible that none of them have been arrested over the years,” said Tyrone Brooks, who helped organize the repeat.
“This is the stain of history, the burden of our soul.”
Brooks, 71, is a former Georgia lawmaker and life-long rights activist.
For him, the reenactment was a compelling call to remind people in the Monroe community every year that injustice has never been corrected.
“We want to sue, we want to close the case, we want to heal, we want reconciliation, but we have to get justice first,” he said.
“Unless we receive justice, we will not be healed and reconciled.”
On July 27, 1946, the coroner put a sheet on the body of a moor beach lynching victim.
According to FBI files obtained by NBC News, more than 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties are suspected of involvement in lynchings.
None of them have been charged.
While the suspects have been at large for decades, civil rights activists say the dual motivation for lynching is well known throughout the town: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court ruling allowed black citizens of Georgia to vote in primaries for the first time later that summer.
According to FBI statistics, around the same time, Roger Malcolm, a black mate farmer, assassinated white landowner Barnet Hirst in a fight — looking like it was for a woman.
Brooks said rumors in the town were that Hearst had slept with Malcolm's wife, Dorothy, and that her baby wasn't her husband's.
The FBI said that on July 25, 1946, prominent white landowner Roy Harrison spent $600 to bail Malcolm out of prison.
Dorothy and her cousins, Mary and George Dorsey, accompanied him to prison.
But as they returned from prison and were nearing Moore Beach Bridge, a mob of lynchings surrounded the car.
“It turns out that Harrison organized and ordered this murder,” an FBI report concluded.
“It is clear that there is a conspiracy between state and local law enforcement, who not only participated in the murder, destroyed the evidence, but also concealed the identity of the witnesses.”
Brooks is very brief.
He said, “This is a vote tragedy.”
“They were killed, and it was the murderer who sent a message to the black people in this community: ‘If you register and vote, you will have the same outcome.’ ”
For nearly a decade, Cassandra Green has been responsible for the annual reenactment of the Moor Beach Bridge lynchings.
Her expression is vivid, gripping, and deeply racist. Many hope that this racism no longer exists in the United States.
It’s hard to see, it’s harder not to look, but Green says that’s the key.
“We don’t want to talk about lynching because lynchings make us face the ugly side of all,” she said.
"But if you don't listen to me, or don't hear me tell you about my experiences, I can't have a relationship with you."
This year’s show began in June, with nearly 30 actors — a dozen whites and the rest black — crammed into a room on the first day to listen to Greene’s release of a rehearsal for an overview of the show.
Wade Marbaugh is Greene's co-director.
He has played the role of the Ku K-Party for many years, but he says the role has never been easy.
“I feel dirty because I’m not a person like that,” Marbau said.
“But I think it’s very important to keep this history alive, because we don’t want to go back to that era.”
In the room, actors Darios Bradshaw and Nick Lascona, who played Roger Malcolm and Barnet Hirst, rehearsed their lines.
At the beginning of the play, Malcolm yells and pushes away Hirst, angry that he slept with his wife, Dorothy.
“I said, get out of my place!”
Lascona hit back.
And then they fought.
Then everyone (at least all the black actors) burst into laughter.
Green laughed the best.
“What’s wrong?” asked Rascona.
He was panicked and confused.
Have I played too much?
“No,” Green said with a laugh.
"I just don't think white people say 'ah' when they hit back."
“Yes,” another black actor quipped.
"Your tone must be tough."
In this way, the energy in the room changed; the feeling of fraternity drove away the feeling of discomfort.
Everyone worked hard to do so, not only to perform the show, but also to commemorate the four victims.
The scene begins again.
This time, when Rascona said the word "ah", the tone was sharp and powerful.
No one laughed.
The replay ended powerfully and quickly.
Screams, gunshots, and then silence.
A woman dressed in a funeral black stood by the body of the actor and sang Billy Haladee’s lament “Strange Fruit.”
Her voice overwlned the other words.
A hundred yards away, about forty spectators were wiping sweat and tears incessantly.
Black and white people accounted for almost half of the audience.
There was a couple who came from Ithaca, New York, to see the show, and many people lived near the road.
Brooks took them to the graves of Malcolm and Dorothy for nearly eight hours, all of whom endured Georgia's uncomfortable wet and hot feelings.
Until this time, the murderer was still a fan. But now, standing in the same land where lynchings took place, there was anxiety in the air.
When the last note of the song disappears, Green asks people to come nearer to examine the bodies played by the actors.
The children leaned down, looked at the fake blood and the corpse, whispering to each other.
“They’re not really dead,” a little boy muttered, as if to remind himself.
After a few minutes, Green thanked the crowd, and then the show ended.
The actor broke the lynching rope and wiped away the tears.
Bradshaw hugged Marbau, the man in the suit who played the head of the Ku K.
Nick Lascona hugged his two colleagues, weeping in their arms; the emotions in the show eventually infected him.
“It doesn’t matter,” one of the women whispered.
“We know that’s not the case in your heart.
You do it for a reason.”
After that, the audience sat down to dinner with the actors.
At the same table, a white couple from Atlanta chatted intimately with a black couple they had just met, talking about a repeat.
Denis Duplinski had a hard time finding words to describe how she felt after watching.
“It’s hard to imagine those horrible words and actions... people like you say it and make it because they look so much like you,” she said.
“For me, it really makes me think that the lynching is still going on,” she added. “Nowadays it’s called a police shooting.”
In the room, Tyrone Brooks sat at the table watching, tasting and regurating with civil rights.
He said he is already planning next year’s show.
“Repetition is an inspiring way to do it because it describes the horrors we’ve experienced, but it’s also very instructive,” he said.
“If you don’t learn from it, this could happen again.
Those who do not study and do not understand their own history are doomed to repeat the mistakes.”
