Scientists at China Air Force Engineering University study laser satellite for removal of space junk
Reference News Network reported on January 18 that Chinese scientists have made a bold and innovative proposal to use large lasers to clean up the clutter of Earth's orbit and destroy old satellites and its sky garbage.
According to the US Newsweek website reported on January 15, researchers at the Chinese Air Force Engineering University have written a paper entitled "Sky-based Laser Clearance Small Scale Space Debris Reorientation Model Study", which describes how space debris can be irradiated by lasers into smaller, less harmful debris through the use of space-based platform lasers.
Space junk has been a concern for the international space agency for years, and NASA has considered a variety of options to track, detect and remove man-made debris.
Ways to remove large-scale space debris include giant nets for cleaning and collecting waste, and magnets that can be used to suck them out of orbit. Chinese scientists conducted laser simulations and concluded that this would be an effective way to clean up Earth's orbit.
The abstract of the paper states: “(The simulation study) provides the necessary theoretical basis for the application of space-based laser space debris removal techniques.”
A 2014 study by U.S. defense giant Lockheed Martin found that there are about 200 threats a day for satellites that are orbiting.
High-speed debris moving along Earth's orbit is seen as a serious threat to future space missions and has been described by European Space Agency experts as a "deadly litany of threats." High-speed debris has continued to increase over the past year.
According to the website of the US "Popular Machinery" monthly website reported on January 17, space is basically empty, but space next to Earth is becoming more and more crowded. Every satellite we send into space will eventually become another piece of debris orbiting the earth, and over time, these pieces will pile up.
The more debris there is, the higher the chance that a satellite that is still functioning will be hit by the debris, which in turn damages or destroys a multi-million dollar investment.
All space agencies have plans to remove space junk in the future.
NASA is considering using jet gas to slow the debris down and deorbit it, and Europe is considering launching a satellite carrying a large net to capture the debris and bring it back to Earth, and the Japanese idea is to capture the debris with an electric chain.
Now, China is also proposing a solution to space junk, that is, using a large laser to shoot floating space junk into less harmful small pieces.
According to a paper published in the German monthly optical journal, installing such a laser on a satellite would be efficient enough to clean up space, at least according to the simulation results.
The only way to prove effectiveness is to test, and there are no such missions yet, but perhaps sooner or later someone will install a laser on a satellite and send it into space.
Once that’s done, we can finally start eliminating the problem of space junk once and for all.
