Latest results from Sweden’s age assessment test for asylum seekers announced
The latest test for asylum seekers in Sweden uses the latest method to assess their age, and the latest results show that more than 80% of the subjects are judged to be over 18 years old, but not everyone believes in its accuracy.
The Swedish National Centre for Forensic Medicine (R?ttsmedicinalverket) began testing earlier this year.
After allegedly failing to accurately assess the age of some of the refugees claiming to be minors, the Swedish Migration Board (Migrationsverket) designed these tests with a view to a more accurate age assessment during the asylum process.
So far, the Swedish Migration Board has sent 6,880 test subjects, and the Forensic Science Center has now published the results of a total of 2,481 test subjects between mid-March 2017 and July 31.
Eighty percent (2002 people) were judged to be 18 years of age or older, but in another 25 tests, the Swedish National Centre for Forensic Science determined that the subjects were “probably 18 years or older.”
In 432 tests, the result was that the person “may be under 18 years old.”
The test is only for people with questionable age.
According to John Glenson of the Center for Forensic Medicine, these results are consistent with those of previous months.
He told The Local: “These figures are not much different from those of the previous months, the numbers are very consistent.”
A higher proportion of cases of persons over the age of 18 do not necessarily mean that these asylum seekers lied about their age.
In May, the center published 581 test results and said 442 cases “indicated that the subject was 18 years of age or older.”
Newspaper Svenska Dagbladet surveyed the results of the 581 published results and found that 243 of them had publicly stated that they would be 18 years of age or older this year.
X-rays of wisdom teeth, MRI scans of joints, and then analysis by dentists and radiologists, this medical evaluation approach is also being questioned in some areas.
One of the skeptics was Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at Caroline College, whose work included assessing people’s biological maturity to determine whether they experienced puberty earlier or later than normal.
He told the newspaper Metro: “I have reason to think that, and I don’t think the measurement used should be like that.
It is very inaccurate to determine the biological age in this way.
If we cannot guarantee accuracy, we should not pretend that we can do it.”
However, Gramson of the Forensic Science Center defended the accuracy of these tests: "The risk of not determining whether a child is an adult is generally very small."
The biggest risk is that the person is just under the age of 18, which is about 10%.
