How will football financial rules affect Neymar’s move to Paris?
The rules aimed at preventing unrestricted spending by big European clubs do not prevent Neymar from moving from Barcelona in Spain to Paris Saint-Germain Football Club (PSG) in France at a record price.
The result was a further relegation of the European Football Association (UEFA) to Paris Saint-Germain Football Club. The European Football Association is the governing body of European football and has the right to ban teams from the much-discussed Champions League.
The introduction of the Financial Fair Play Rules (FFP) by UEFA in 2011 means that Paris Saint-Germain will eventually have to prove that Neymar’s transfer is funded without causing huge losses.
The club has paid 222 million euros ($262 million) just to pay the Brazilian player for the release, and Neymar’s salary will be as high as tens of millions of dollars a year.
Here are some of the financial implications of Neymar’s move to France.
Given that the team is funded by the well-funded Qatari ruling family, Paris Saint-Germain Football Club can certainly sign Neymar with cash and include him in teams with other stars.
Clubs can spend a lot of money on players, but they have to use legitimate sources of income to make up for the huge amount of money they spend to break even in their football-related business.
The Financial Fair Play Rules were conceived by Michel Platini after being elected president of UEFA in 2007.
The former French player believes that for clubs that are heavily indebted in pursuit of success, if banks or everyone withdraws their support funds, they are in fact cheating and putting the club at risk of destruction.
In 2011, the focus of the Rules shifted from the club’s debt problems to the club’s loss situation monitoring.
The change means that Roman Abramovich’s business model, when he bought Chelsea in 2003, buying a club with potential and then spending heavily to improve the team and build it into a global brand is now facing a more demanding situation.
During the three-year Rules assessment period up to 2018, the club could lose €30 million.
Despite Abu’s disparaging bid by the then president in 2015, UEFA’s successor, Aleksander Ceferin, remains committed to stopping excessive spending.
“Of course the Rules haven’t lapsed yet, and we’re definitely going to strengthen the regulations of the future,” Andrea Traverso, who is in charge of the rules, told The Associated Press last week.
Although Paris Saint-Germain Football Club will pay Neymar's buyout clause in one lump sum, it can also be allocated for the purpose of accounting during the term of the contract.
Neymar has signed a five-year deal, so transfer fees are likely to show a fee of €44.4 million in the annual accounts for the next five years.
The first wave of rules imposed in 2014 imposed imposed the toughest sanctions on Paris Saint-Germain FC and the Abu Dhabi-owned Manchester City club.
Paris Saint-Germain Football Club was fined 60 million euros ($82 million at the time exchange rate) and later reduced to 20 million euros, and asked for the 2014-15 Champions League to reduce the number of players to 21 instead of the normal 25 players in the 2014-15 Champions League.
UEFA is watching to stare at clubs that are trying to increase revenue and deceive financial regulators by pegging to club owners.
While Qatari companies can sponsor Paris Saint-Germain FC, UEFA will not consider it a legitimate income if the amount of sponsorship is deemed to exceed the standard market price.
That’s what happened in 2014, when UEFA ruled that the amount of money Qatar Tourism Board sponsored to Paris Saint-Germain Football Club had been overstated.
It is reported that part of Neymar's revenue at Paris Saint-Germain Football Club may come from the payment made by the 2022 Qatar World Cup organizing committee.
However, both Paris-Saint-Germain and the organizing committee have denied that Neymar will be ambassador for the World Cup, and it is easy for UEFA’s regulators to make such a move.
The recent sanctions imposed on Paris Saint-Germain mean that UEFA will be more wary of any attempt to circumvent the rules.
People familiar with the matter said on Thursday that UEFA had not had any prior discussions with Paris-Saint-Germain on Neymar's transfer.
All of them were only in contact with The Associated Press in an unnamed capacity because they were not authorized to discuss the situation of Paris Saint-Germain Football Club.
According to the last published accounts, the operating income of Paris Saint-Germain Football Club in 2015-16 was 542.4 million euros, and the profit was more than 10 million euros.
The accounts for the previous fiscal year have not yet been published.
Paris Saint-Germain Football Club expects Neymar’s joining to be a boon for sponsorship events, franchises and shirt sales.
The club expects revenue to grow by at least 30% after signing Neymar.
It is clear that the Spanish league is deeply angry to see one of the most famous players leave, trying to hinder Neymar's move and claiming that Paris Saint-Germain Football Club violated the rules.
La Liga president Javier Tebas told Spanish newspaper AS that “this is a clear example of a ‘financial doping’, the club and the country are alike”, referring to Qatar, which has ultimate ownership of Paris-based St. Germain Football Club.
Arsenal team (who owns all the American sports tycoons) manager Arsene Wenger has reservations about state-funded clubs and La Liga.
“It’s a consequence of ownership, and it’s revolutionizing the entire ecology of football over the last 15 years,” Wenger said on Thursday.
“Once the country owns the club, then anything can happen.
This will make it very difficult to comply with the Rules, because for a country there are many different ways or interests in which a big player is required to represent a country.”
