NHS England announced that Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP), a drug that can be taken before sex, has been shown to reduce the risk of infection in high-risk groups by around 86%. The health service will now deliver the drug to an estimated 10,000 people through a three-year preliminary trial.
It agreed to fund the trial after the Court of Appeal upheld the High Court ruling last year. The ruling said the NHS was entitled to pay PrEP for the cost of the drug despite the NHS's claim that local authorities should fund the drug.
The move, announced on Thursday, was described by NHS chief executive Simon Stevens as a "significant new intervention", while the National AIDS Trust (NAT) described it as a "critical moment".
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be the first to register sexual health clinics. More clinics will be added in October, followed by a full implementation in England in April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV drug that is taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Trials have shown that PrEP can significantly reduce HIV transmission in people at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before sex means that there are enough specific medications in the body to prevent HIV infection.
This medication can be taken daily or two hours before sexual intercourse.
Those eligible for treatment included gay, bisexual men, transgender people, and positive HIV carriers who had not successfully received treatment.
The clinic will identify eligible participants who agreed to the trial, including those who are unknown to men, women, transgender people and their sexual partners who are infected with HIV status with HIV.
People who live and register as a general practitioner in England can also register at their local sexual health clinic.
The scheme will cost £10 million, while NHS England has signed a contract to procure the drugs this week after an international competitive procurement.
The trial aims to assess the full potential of PrEP by collecting clinical evidence on a large sample basis on how it is localized, absorbed, and implemented.
“This major new intervention should be a broad and increasingly successful complement to and strengthen HIV prevention.”
This is yet another milestone that has been worthwhile for more than 30 years of action to make progress in addressing the major health challenges of humanity.”
Deborah King, chief executive of the UK AIDS Trust (NAT), said: “This is a critical time in the fight against AIDS.
If it does target people in need and at risk, pre-exposure prophylaxis offers the possibility of changing the HIV epidemic in the UK.
Starting in September, people at risk of HIV will be given a new, permissioned tool through the NHS-funded trial in England, which is truly self-contained, without consultation with sexual partners, which will bring improvements to the lives of many people.
We agree with the announcement.”
Ian Green, chief executive of the Terence Higgins Trust, said: “The priority now is to ensure that trials are rolled out quickly across the country and that none of the people living with HIV are left behind.
Now that we have purchased the PrEP trial, we are ready to protect more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV.”
Shadow Public Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: “After months of delays and government delays, the start of PrEP’s first trial is welcome and should have come sooner.
Evidence shows how this drug can change as part of our approach to preventing HIV and stopping the spread of this deadly infectious disease.
This trial will allow us to further and fully understand the advantages of PrEP.
It is now important to launch the trial as soon as possible across the country to protect people exposed to HIV and to help us go one step further to end the spread of HIV in society.”
