High quality of life: application of loft and clever design to make the Count's Palace small apartment a spacious home
Joanne Ray, a former banker who was keen to renovate her house, moved from her Grand House on Knightsbridge to a small apartment in the Count's Palace in 2014.
This apartment is located on the first floor of an elegant Queen Anne terrace – Joanne didn’t pack her bags and sell it, which is a powerful testament to the new design.
“Before that, my ex-boyfriend and I were living in a larger house on Knightsbridge,” Joanne said.
“I was looking for the right house.
I saw this apartment in the Count's Palace, and its ceiling was also very high.
I liked it, and made an offer that day."
Since the first time you’ve seen the room, the 1,000-square-foot apartment has now been overhauled.
Originally a studio with a complex layout — requiring passage through the kitchen to walk to the bedroom — Joanne wanted to add storage space and loft to make the most of the ceiling height.
“I want high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
That’s what I asked,” she said.
To this end, she hired Elfan Azadi from Duck & Shed Architecture and Design Studio (Notting Hill) to use the 12.5-foot ceiling to build a home. This home is not only a development project, but also a place where Joanne lives.
The ceiling is not high enough to add up to two up and down spaces, so the architectural challenge is to create a high enough to stand up attic.
Elfan had to be creative in order to solve the problem.
“The steel structure is quite complex,” he explained.
“We have to arrange the space to be displayed up and down, and there is no need to shrug the back of the bow.
It’s not just about building a simple platform, but starting these steels to put them at the right height to achieve functionality.”
Through this arrangement, Elfan was able to obtain two full-body high rooms in the space - which can add a lot of interesting elements.
The loft features retro copper windows from the Retrouvius brand overlooking the enchanting living area.
Golden furniture with mirrors, silver piece furniture and Serge Mouille retro lighting lay the overall style.
The use of mirrors plays an important role in increasing the atmosphere, space and light.
Put a mirror on both ends of the short corridor to make it look longer.
In the kitchen, the splash board with a mirror is like a window to another room.
At the porch, small lattices with mirrors provide Joanne with storage space for tableware and glassware.
The beautiful living room has a fascinating sense of space and can be put away when the kitchen is unused.
The kitchen is not fresh.
But what makes this folding kitchen unique is a garage-style lift door.
“Some engineering knowledge is involved here,” Elfan explains of the reinforced MDF door.
“It’s a balancing principle, so when you push the door, it’s easy to slide.”
Thanks to the clever use of space and storage, Joanne received an additional 16 square meters, an additional bedroom and an improved layout.
“Ultimately, what you’re selling is the size of the house — or your property valuation is based on the size of the house,” Elfan said.
“Basically, a real estate agent walks into a room and calculates it based on floor size.”
They will try to increase the space occupied by using high-quality materials at the same time, thus bringing a sense of luxury to this space.
Elfan said, “Materials are hand-picked by you, and therefore help to create emotional bonds at home.”
“You don’t love the power on the wall.
These things are important, but they won't hold your heartstrings."
It turns out that with good design and extra space, standard apartments can be transformed to amaze you.
In fact, you may choose to live like Joanne.
