Two brothers stage $500 million real estate empire battle
Forty years after the founding of their Italian family, the brothers battled for one of Victoria’s largest real estate empires worth more than $500 million.
Colin De Lutis, a former director and developer of Carleton Football Club, lives in a mansion in the Tukkala district, and the three doors are at the residence of his brother Paul. The latter took him to the Supreme Court over the division of their real estate and business assets.
Paul has wanted to break away from the family business since 2014, but the two brothers have been arguing fiercely over the asset split in the Supreme Court.
The brothers and their mother own a total of 38 real estate, worth more than $500 million, which have accumulated since the family bought Smith Street in the Collingwood district in 1973.
There, the family founded Westco Jeans and grew it to 160 retail chains.
In 1999, the company sold for $85 million.
The money was then put into real estate. Currently, the De Rutis family's portfolio of assets includes city office buildings, Brunswick and Sorrento development projects, Gold Coast and Bühler Hill apartments, and suburban shopping malls.
According to an agreement with his late father, Colin, who was called the “principal promoter and dominant figure” of the De Lutis family by his younger brother Paul, had about two-thirds of the company’s assets, while Paul made up about a third.
Documents filed with the court state that Colin owned $316 million worth of property and $176 million worth of property Paul.
Paul argues that the separation of real estate and cash is the crux of the negotiations.
“Colin’s proposal for the division of property left what I think is the best,” he wrote in an initial court affidavit in 2015.
On Friday, after several failed mediation, the Supreme Court held its first hearing.
Now, the two brothers are still fighting for control of the existing business, and Paul said Colin has kicked him out.
Colin denied this and accused Paul of poor management of certain real estate.
In an early affidavit submitted by Colin, he expressed a desire to resolve the dispute.
"My Italian tradition dictates that family is the most important option. My Italian ancestry determines that family is the most important," he wrote.
The cost of the case has been rising, along with hundreds of pages of affidavits, emails, and corporate reports from companies such as Deloitte, Pitcher Partners, Charter Keck Cramer, Allan Myers, QC, and senior lawyers from both parties.
Ms. de Rutis and her late husband Luigi are both Italian immigrants. They have been running mass restaurants and deli since the late 1950s, and bought a store in Brunswick in the early 1970s.
They used collateral to buy the Collingwood property, where Colin opened the family’s first jeans store.
Colin said, “When I was in high school,” and he started Westco there, “Paul was very young (about 10 years old) at the time.”
Anna de Rutis said she and Luigi, who died in 2012, wanted to pass on their property to her son in peace.
“Luigi often told me that he would never want his brothers to go to court in the end,” she wrote.
The other two brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer members of the De Rutis Group of Companies, and Colin said Mark paid him $10 million when he left the company and $26 million to Luke.
Paul says that both Luke and Mark “dissare to their property division terms.”
According to a biography published in 2015 by TV star Eddie McGuire, Colin has kept a low profile despite being a former AFL club board member.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul, as well as their lawyers, on Friday.
However, only Colin responded by text message. He said that because the case had been brought to court, "I really can't say much."
“It is very, very sad that my brother Paul chose to sue me and bring our family affairs to court,” he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote in a court filing that he had tried to meet his brother’s request.
“Our father did not want to see Paul and me end up in such a dispute,” he said, adding that he “still holds out hope for the settlement of the dispute.”
On Friday, that hope seemed to be dashed.
“Our issues will be resolved through the courts in the near future,” Colin wrote.
