Trump's new chief of staff plans to limit the president's media time
Others have tried, but all failed.
John F. Kelly might actually be able to do it.
If that’s true, he’s the first.
According to Politico, the new White House chief of staff plans to restrict the flow of information to President Trump — including news media reports — in a bid to keep big bosses calmer.
Here’s a quote from journalist Josh Dawcy:
“When the new White House Chief of Staff, John F. Kelly, began his first day of work, gathered with senior officials to discuss, he pointed out that he wanted to address one of the main issues that President Trump had in the White House: the bad information that flowed into the hands of the president.”
Kelly told the officials that receiving good information would help the president make better decisions, so the information needed to go through his hands — in writing or in the form of a briefing.
Kelly’s diagnosis may seem like a model, but others have tried to tame it by spying on Trump’s media time, but all ended in failure.
President Trump’s television addiction has a long history — now in the White House, his habit of watching TV is still deepening.
In February, former campaign adviser Sam Naberg told Politico: “If candidate Trump is frustrated by unfair reporting, it will be helpful to let him know that he has also received positive reporting in credible channels.”
Politico’s Tara Palmery wrote at the time that “based on the experience of the six former campaign officials, the point of controlling Trump’s Twittering habits is to ensure that the media messages he personally receive contain a certain amount of praise.”
That's no problem at all.
But Trump’s Twitter habit was once “controlled” that it was ridiculous.
Perhaps these campaign officials know something we don’t know – that is, if it weren’t for their interference, Trump’s tweets would have been even more raging.
We may never know the tweets Trump didn’t send.
If his staff can save him from the water and fire, even if only a few times, their efforts are worth it.
But no one can stop Trump from causing controversy.
Part of the problem is that in a White House of competing blocs, people promote their worldviews and push their careers by handing over to Trump sources that may or may not be reliable.
Politico — all about the story — reported in May on advisers’ penchant for strategically providing dubious information to the president.
This is an example of what journalist Shane Goodmancher described:
Current and former Trump officials say Trump’s response to negative news footage such as volcanic eruptions, especially those with damaging information leaks, would be frantically wanting to find out where it came from.
At the end of February, someone maliciously copied an article on the website of the network agitator Charles C. Johnson, GotNews.com, to the president, accusing Deputy Chief of Staff Katie Walsh of the White House of “a source of a lot of information leaks,” which Trump said at the time.
Even if Johnson had been permanently banned from Twitter for harassment, he had not provided any concrete evidence, and he had blown up a lot of false allegations, which were later publicly denied.
Trump read the article and started asking officials about Walsh's situation."
Goodmancher also said that then-Chief of Staff Reines Prybass and White House Secretary Rob Porter “had tried to build a system to manage and record documents received by Trump.”
What is the result?
Kelly was going to do the same thing, in three months.
He may be able to prove that he is a more effective manager than Prybas, but Trump is still the impulsive Trump, and his aides are still competing with each other for influence.
These timeless factors make Kelly’s task more difficult.
