Italy takes tough stance on NGO migrant rescue ship
Italy has warned NGOs operating migrant rescue ships in the Mediterranean that they will not be allowed to continue to implement the rescue without signing new rules of action.
In an interview with the Turin daily newspaper News, the Minister of the Interior, Marco Minniti, stated: “If NGOs do not sign new norms of conduct, it is difficult to see how they will continue.”
Minniti’s warning came a day after Italian officials detained him on suspicion that the crew of a ship on a ship by the German aid group Youth Rescue was actually colluding with human traffickers to help illegal immigrants.
The aid group has only been in operation for a year and declined to comment on the specific subject of the allegations by Italian prosecutor Ambrogio Cartosio.
“Saving lives is and will be the most important thing for us, and we regret that we cannot operate in the search and rescue zone at this time,” the group said in a statement on social media.
“After all the information has been collected, we can only assess all the allegations and the situation at this time.”
Italian officials have been monitoring the Iuventa, a ship organized by Youth Relief, since October.
Its crew is suspected of carrying migrants carried by human traffickers directly from small boats and allowed smugglers to flee in haste and re-utilize the ships.
According to the prosecutor's records, at least one such meeting allegedly took place 1.3 miles off the coast of Libya. The contents of the document were published by Italian media.
Its crew is suspected of blatant disregard for the authority of the Italian Coast Guard, which oversees rescue operations in the area for humanitarian reasons other than any other motive.
According to the Code of Conduct, vessels such as Iuventa clearly require an Italian police officer to supervise their activities on board.
Currently, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have agreed to comply with the Code of Conduct: Save the Children, Malta, Malta, and Pro-Activa Open Arms in Spain.
The latter said on Thursday it considered the new rules, while unnecessary, but acceptable because they did not bring any “significant changes or impediments” to their rescue operations.
Among the organizations that refused to sign was the Nobel Prize-winning organization Doctors Without Borders (MSF).
At the same time, Minniti said the sharp drop in the number of migrants arriving in Italy in recent weeks shows that efforts to strengthen the Libyan coast and unite local mayors are beginning to bear fruit.
“In recent days, we have started to see the light at the end of the tunnel,” the minister said.
He unveiled plans for this month’s in-depth talks: discussing economic development with Libyan mayors and Chad, Niger and Mali on how to reduce the number of migrants leaving the country for Europe.
