Dinosaurs use disguises to hide from enemies
At first glance, it looks terrible, but it looks like a statue.
Researchers have published the first results of an inconceivable fossil of rhino-sized, rhino-sized organisms found by Canadian miners, pointing out that the fossil is well-preserved, so experts call it the “Mona Lisa of the dinosaur world.”
The fossil is so well preserved that it can even determine that its scaly skin is reddish-brown in color. This suggests that it had some "troublesome experiences".
The report in the journal Current Biology described it as “the best-preserved clad dinosaur ever found, and one of the best dinosaur specimens in the world.”
The fossil is a newly discovered species of nodule dragon that lived between the mid-Cracypic Period of 110 million and 212 million years ago.
Its state of preservation is so well-preserved that it shocked researchers, who described it as “really breathtaking.”
According to National Geographic, the herbivorous clad dinosaur fossil is the best-preserved dinosaur fossil of its kind ever found.
On March 21, 2011, Shawn Funk discovered the fossil while mining at the Sumberlo Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada.
At that moment he came across something that seemed to be different from the rocks around him, and he decided to take a closer look.
The fossils he found were sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology in Canada.
It took the researchers six years to reveal the beast inside the 2,500-pound (1,100-kilogram) cavity.
After such a hard work, the final results are now being announced.
"If you look at it, you almost believe it's sleeping," said Caleb Brown, a scientist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum. The creature is on display at the exhibition.
“It will be one of the most beautiful and best-preserved dinosaur specimens in the history of science – the Mona Lisa in the dinosaur world.”
By studying their skin, the researchers found that the herbivorous creature, though clothed in armor, like a walking tank, could be a major threat from carnivorous dinosaurs.
The armored dinosaurs used red and white camouflage to avoid predators, and used concealment known as "anti-shade", a method used by many modern animals.
In this way, experts say, it is better able to blend in with its surroundings to avoid enemies, suggesting it was preyed on by larger dinosaurs.
The 110-million-year-old creature, a member of the thuneiplankosaur family, made headlines for the first time in May and is currently on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
After Mark Mitchell, a museum technician who was one of the team members, took 7,000 hours to elaborate on the behemoth, the researchers now study it and named it “Borealopelta Markmitchelli.”
The samples are so well preserved that Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists can record the patterns and shapes of scales and armor on their bodies.
They found “anti-shade” techniques, a common form of defense in the animal kingdom, which means that the backs of the species are darker than the color of their sides.
Although “antishade” is common, the results of the discovery are surprising, because the dinosaur species is much larger than the existing animals that use anti-shading.
This dinosaur faced the pressure of being hunted by carnivorous dinosaurs, thus evolving in a favorable direction, allowing it to hide in the confrontation as a means of survival.
However, most of the existing animals that use anti-shading, such as deer, zebra, or armadillo, are as small and fragile as prey, indicating that the creature is under real pressure to survive.
“The wild predation of large heavy armored dinosaurs shows how dangerous Cretaceous carnivorous dinosaurs are,” Brown said.
Chemical analysis of the organic complex in its scales also showed that the dinosaur's skin color was reddish-brown.
Scientists are continuing to study clues to the creature’s life, including the stomach inclusions it retains to find out what the last food to be eaten.
They believe that dinosaurs fell into the river when they died, then rushed into the sea and finally sank back into the sea.
At the time, Alberta’s climate was as warm as it is in southern Florida today, and rivers and oceans could be deeper inland than they are today.
“This nodule dragon is truly amazing because it is completely covered with preserved scaly skin and has been preserved in dimensional space so far in dimensional space, so that its original shape can be preserved,” Brown said.
“As a result, the creature is now shaped almost the same as it was during the Cretaceous.
You don't have to use too much imagination to rebuild it; if you look at it, you almost believe it's sleeping."
The Cretaceous period was a time when large, two-leggedropod dinosaurs roamed the earth.
