It has two 20-inch-long sharp corners that protrud from the shoulders.
Researchers believe that the herbivorous lindraped dinosaurs were active in what is now western Canada, after which they were washed into the sea by rivers that erupted in floodwaters.
However, the dinosaur buried the seabed so that the armor can be preserved in its entirety.
The fossil remains of this particular sample are so well preserved that the remaining skin still covers the uneven pieces of nails on the dinosaur skulls.
As Michael Greshko wrote in National Geographic, this degree of preservation is as rare as the winning color.
The more I looked, the more I thought it was unbelievable.
