A @TheePharoah user kept pushing her the dynamic Times.
The St. Louis-area rapper live-streamed the death of Michael Brown. Michael Brown, an 18-year-old unarmed black man, was killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a picture of Brown lying on the street with his body missing in vital signs, and his body lay in the street for four hours.
“Crazy,” Ferrell thought.
But death is nothing new for her and her community.
She put down her phone and didn’t open it again until that evening to read about the crowds on Canfield Avenue.
There were police footage and photos of people shouting, and a photo of a man who claimed to be Brown’s father, which read: “The Ferguson police officer just killed my unarmed son!”
She saw a message from the scene of a police officer standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, she said, another police officer raised his rifle and screamed, "I'll kill all of you... the animals."
“It’s not normal,” Ferrer recalled.
“This is not a typical murder we take for granted.”
At that moment, I felt shudder.
I was angry, crying."
She booked a return flight and went home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., she picked up her six-year-old daughter from her father’s house and decided to head for Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrer and Ferguson over the next three years was the subject of a new documentary, “Whose Street?”, which opens in theaters on Aug. 11.
