When Ferrer and his daughter (wearing a floral dress and crown accessory) drove to Ferguson, the two revisited the topic they had discussed countless times before that morning—“on the black experience and the black condition.”
“Do you remember when I taught you that black people had to fight for their faith?” she recalled.
“We are going to Ferguson now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy, which is not right.
“I had to take her with me,” Ferrell said later.
“What happened today is the climax of everything that has happened in the past.
She wants to know, see and rise from this.
Not only does she need to develop well in activism and organization, but she needs to understand the different dimensions of the black experience and the black situation, and what we have to do to be free and free.
Even though I was lucky enough to give her a racist experience she hadn’t personally experienced, she was no different from other black girls.
If I protect her in this matter, I feel like I'm hurting her."
They arrived at Ferguson's first stop at a site opposite the South Florida Sand Road Police Station. The militant waited until the result of Officer Darren Wilson's final non-prosecution, and the site became their camp.
Ferrer and her daughter contacted a local business owner who made a bagged lunch.
They prepared the bag, which was responsible for passing it on to the protesters.
Slowly, Ferrer began to form a new type of activism.
She said, "My activism changed completely after August 9th." When she was an undergraduate at Missouri State University in St. Louis, she was president of the Minority Nurses Association, focusing on food justice and health disparities in black communities.
“I have no organizational experience.
That's how it all came.”
A few weeks later, Ferrer met with film co-director Sabah Foleyan at a night parade.
Fulayan said she and her director of photography, Lucas Alvarado Faller, “just wanted to document” what happened.
Ferrer had a question in his mind: “Do you want to record or do you want to find a story you can use?”
This suspicion stems from many of these cases: People — often white — go into a community to benefit from their pain and tenacity.
As Foleyan explained in a recent interview, “We heard that the native people in Ferguson didn’t focus their voices, and we wanted to do it differently.”
Forlayan has been in contact with co-director Dimon Davis, a regional artist known for his activism against death row inmates.
His involvement led Ferrell to join the “Whose Street?” project team with six other locals, and for several years after Brown’s shooting.
“This documentary is not about someone talking to us or talking to us, this is what we’re saying,” Davis said.
“I’m mainly concerned about how these characters are presented, because that’s how I’m presented.”
While the goal was not to focus on Ferrer’s experience — it was to show that the movement was “not about the savior leader, but about community cohesion,” Forlayan said — it turned out she was the most open of the film’s participants.
As a result, “Whose Street?” is a surprising account of Ferrer’s personal life, such as falling in love and getting married.
“I feel naked,” Ferrell laughed as she first saw the finished product.
“But I understand that to do this work and humanize black people, there has to be a certain degree of vulnerability.”
In addition, Ferrer’s story reaffirms and repositions the role of black queer women in the broader Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the movement’s three founders — who created #BlackLivesMatter on social media following the 2012 shooting of black teenager Trevoron Martin — were identified as queer.
