"Although she's on the front lines, it's no coincidence. Because in these crossroads lives, as a black queer woman, you have a lot to do.
Through the screen, you can feel her energy."
Meanwhile, in Ferguson, news cameras are long gone, but strained race relations between the community and the police persist.
Ferrer was given more than two-and-a-half-year suspended sentences for trying to block the highway during a parade.
She described the socio-political climate in the area of what she called home: “a mess.”
Still, since she took to the streets of Ferguson three years ago, she has insisted on the chants she has worked to remember.
“We have a responsibility to fight for freedom.
We have a responsibility to win.
