Amy Errett once wanted to investigate employee well-being at her e-commerce startup, but the survey didn’t work.
The responses received are often vague, unhelpful, and even worse, deceptive.
Even though she promised anonymity, some employees still distrust the process.
Ms. Erret, which manages the 75-person San Francisco e-commerce hair care company, said she “lacks consistency and objectivity in the responses.”
So she called for help.
A new batch of HR startups has sprung up to help companies understand how employees feel.
They build and license software specifically designed to measure employee engagement, allowing companies to quickly conduct polls on specific teams and population groups, provide anonymity and complaint hotlines for employees, and in some cases allow whistleblowers to bypass executives reporting directly to boards.
“Right now, you can track your health with tools like Strava and Fitbit, but where’s the company’s Fitbit?” said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Redwood City startup Glint. Glint’s software analytics tools are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Within three years, she used Glint to gain more insight into what employees think and feel.
In addition to rapid surveys and polls for specific teams, Glint offers a company heat map, which units complain the most, and which managers approve scores low, at a glance — which gives her insight into why.
Companies are beginning to realize that they must be skilled in controlling the company's workplace culture so as not to become the next Uber. Former Uber employees previously published a blog post describing the harassment environment, and these speakers were punished by the company, and Uber was then caught up in a scandal.
For startups like Glint, this desire to do so is a money-and-go business opportunity.
According to Let’s Talk Payments, the global governance, regulatory and compliance industry could be worth more than $11.87 billion by 2020.
Denver, Colorado, a startup focused on helping companies prevent and detect bad behavior, saw an increase in interest and activity in this area during Uber’s reputation tarnished earlier this year.
Convercent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber recently signed up as a customer.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customized “diagnostic” surveys, collect confidential responses in real time, and view heat maps of their problem areas.
Convercent also provides an anonymous texting hotline to allow employees to report bad behavior.
If the chairman is implicated, the complaint will go directly to the board.
Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of Convercent, said: “The Court of Public Opinion has usurped the power of regulators.
If a company is found to be bad at treating its employees or acting unethically, even if regulators don’t step in, it could face high consequences of consumer boycotts, employee churn and involvement in lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain with more than 2,500 employees across more than 500 locations, has been using Convercent for more than a year to ensure employees understand work guidelines and procedures and provide easy access to corporate headquarters.
Until then, if employees want to report a problem, they must find a phone number or email from the company headquarters, file a formal complaint, and hope that the headquarters can take it seriously.
It’s often a daunting and unsettling experience, says James Witlano, Ruby Tuesday’s general counsel, who believes there’s no good way to track employee complaints.
But now the company uses Convercent to more quickly identify and address issues that were previously unknown to executives in remote offices, cities or states — such as discrimination, harassment, or unfair wage behavior.
“I can get a closer, 360-degree view of the work experience,” says Vitrano, who runs the Ruby Tuesday risk management team.
“We are protecting our shareholders from employment litigation.”
Quinlan said that after the collapse of the accounting firm in Andorran due to the safety scandal, companies began to pay more attention to ethics, values and employee engagement since 2002.
But it wasn’t until “social media went into its own world” that companies realized they couldn’t stop their revelations from spreading virally online.
“Before using technology to monitor ethics, people see hope as a strategy,” he said.
