Does meat, dairy and chocolate help relieve inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)?
The meat and chocolate may sound like a nightmare for your digestive system.
But a new study shows the opposite: A diet rich in meat and dairy products can help alleviate symptoms associated with inflammatory bowel disease patients.
The incurable disease has a life impact on about 1.3 million Americans and about 300,000 Britons, causing stomach cramps and bloating, recurrent or bleeding diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Researchers at the University of Washington often advise patients to avoid eating meat and dairy products to relieve symptoms, but researchers have found that the protein’s key amino acid, tryptophan, helps promote immune cell growth, and these cells boost the tolerance of the gut.
Lead researcher Dr. Marco Colonna explains that immune cells patrol the gut to ensure that harmful microbes hidden in food don’t crept into the body.
Maintain a balance between the inflammatory cells and those that enhance tolerance, protecting the body without damaging various sensitive and vulnerable tissues.
When the equilibrium state is too biased towards inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease may occur.
In the experiment, it was found that an immune-boosting cell appeared in mice that carried special bacteria.
Bacteria need tryptophan, one of the components of the protein, to form the appearance of the cell.
Professor Colonna said: “We established a link between a bacterial population ( Lactobacillus reuteri, which is a normal part of the gut microbiota) and the development of a population that promotes tolerance.
The more tryptophan consumed in the diet, the more immune cells they had.
He suggested that if humans used the same method, i.e. a combination of Lactobacillus and tryptophan-rich diets, might form a more tolerant, less inflammatory gut environment.
Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas, a postdoctoral researcher who studied a type of immune cell that enhances tolerance, did not find that one group of mice studied had such cells, but the same strain was raised separately.
She suspects that this difference is related to the gut microbiota (referring to the bacteria, viruses and fungi that usually live in the gastrointestinal tract) community.
DNA sequencing of the mice’s cholesterol found that six bacterial populations were present in mice with immune cells, but not in mice without immune cells.
Rats are raised in a sterile environment, so they lack gut microbes and cannot develop such immune cells, and those with Lactobacillus pt. leptitius produce immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers cultured Lactobacillus in the liquid and then transferred a small amount of the bacteria-free liquid to the immature immune cells isolated from the mice.
The immune cell develops into a cell with tolerance.
When the active ingredient is purified from the liquid, it can be shown that the active ingredient is a by-product of tryptophan metabolism, called indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the rat feed, the number of such cells increased by about 50%, but when the tryptophan level was halved, the number of cells was cut in half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explains that people, like mice, have the same tolerance-enhancing cells, and most of us have Lactobacillus in our gastrointestinal tract.
Whether humans, like mice in experiments, can induce cell development of tryptophan by-products from Lactobacillus in vitro bacteria in the body, is not known, but gene defects related to tryptophan have been found in patients with inflammatory bowel disease.
“The development of these cells may be exactly what we want, because these cells can control the inflammatory response on the inner surface of the gut,” she said.
It can be said that the high level of tryptophan present in Lactobacillus may lead to an increase in the number of strains.
