Is China's household debt ratio close to that of the United States, and what's more frightening than not being able to afford a home is that it can't pay off debt?
Recently, everyone is discussing what changes in real estate policy have recently changed, is the real estate policy loosened again?
However, when we are worried about real estate prices, worried about macroeconomic regulation and control, and worried about the future trend of the real estate market, the People's Daily once again wrote an article, the last time we specifically discussed the "People's Daily" comment on the adjustment of real estate regulation, and now the People's Daily article is a more serious topic than buying a house, is it even if you can afford to buy a house, you have to get a debt?
Today, we’re going to talk about a bigger problem than buying a house: paying off the loan.
China's Growing Housing Debt Crisis
According to the data in the article, in November 2017, the National Financial and Development Laboratory of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences and the National Balance Sheet Research Center released the "third quarter China deleveraging process report", which pointed out that the leverage ratio of the residential sector continued to rise from 47.4% in the second quarter of 2017 to 48.6% in the third quarter, up 1.3 percentage points, and increased by 3.8 percentage points in the first three quarters of 2017.
The proportion of debt in the entire real economy of the residential sector has increased, and the leverage ratio has risen rapidly.
The study shows that the debt of Chinese households in financial institutions is mainly consumer loans, accounting for about two-thirds of the debt of residents, which is about twice that of operating loans.
Among them, in consumer loans, medium- and long-term loans, mainly housing loans, account for about 80%, but from the incremental point of view, short-term consumer loans grow faster and are higher than medium- and long-term loans.
In addition, China's household debt ratio only counts the total amount of credit that the family sector receives from financial institutions, while Chinese households have many private loans, including borrowing from relatives and friends, and there is a large-scale hidden debt.
According to statistics from the Suning Institute of Finance, the leverage ratio of Chinese residents was only 3% in 1996 and only 18% in 2008, but the leverage ratio of residents began to show rapid growth since 2008, doubling to 36.4% in just six years. By the third quarter of 2017, the leverage ratio of residents had reached 48.6%.
In May last year, HSBC released a survey of nearly 10,000 respondents across nine countries.
The report was conducted among “millennial” young people in nine countries (born between 1980 and 2000).
According to the report, China's post-80s and post-90s youth homeownership rate is as high as 70%, far ahead of second-place Mexico (46%), and twice the level of the US indicator (35%).
These data tell us a very likely problem, that is, compared to the inability to buy a house, the largest potential "gray rhinoceros" in China at this stage is expected to be unable to repay the debt.
Why is the housing debt crisis the most serious problem?
As we have analyzed before, although we have been saying that Chinese house prices are higher, but compared to other countries in the world, China's housing ownership rate is actually quite high, so not so much the high house prices can not afford to buy a house, I am afraid now to ask a lot of friends is do you still have to get a loan?
We look at the world's real estate market, China's real estate market started late, in addition to what we said before Hainan, there has not been a major real estate crisis, but just ten years ago, the origin of the 2008 world financial tsunami is the real estate crisis in the United States.
The reason for the real estate crisis in the United States is attributed to two houses: Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac.
At that time, in the golden age of the United States, real estate companies sold their houses to low-income people in the United States at that time in order to expand sales, and when the US economy was good, the real estate market was also booming, but the good news was not long, with the stagnation of growth in the US economy, causing the income of home buyers to decline, so a large number of household consumer spending began to decline.
However, the current situation in the United States at that time is part of the financial assets and real estate assets of American household assets, almost all of the low-income groups in the United States are real estate, and most of the assets of the top 20% of the high-income groups are financial assets, resulting in the higher the debt ratio of the poorer the real estate in the United States.
A serious fact is that these people are bought when the economy is better, so the money to pay the mortgage is also calculated in terms of their better income, when the income has declined, the pressure of mortgages not only did not reduce or even because some subprime mortgage plans have become floating, so the real estate problems of these American families have gradually evolved into real estate crisis.
So some people because the income is too low to pay the mortgage, so the bank began to recover the property, when the bank from the delinquent loan buyers to recover the property, they will be sold at a very low price, resulting in the region's house prices gradually decline, this process triggered a further decline in house prices, formed a vicious circle, when the house price fell to a certain extent, more and more buyers found that the value of their houses even lower than their own loans, so there are more people to stop repayment, and caused more bad debts.
Thus, a vicious circle is formed:
“The economy is sluggish – incomes are falling – some people can’t afford to pay off their mortgages – banks sell their homes at low prices – house prices are down – more people stop paying off their mortgages – banks are selling – house prices are falling...”
And the problem is not only so, because the price of the house continues to fall, we stop repaying the loan to the bank is not after you have no debt, if the bank auction house to get the money is not enough for you to owe the bank's loan, then you still need to pay back the money, simply say you use the down payment of 600,000, loan 2.4 million to buy a house worth 3 million at the time, when the house price fell to the house is only worth 2 million, you no longer repay the house to the bank, after the bank auction house, you not only lost your own down payment.
As a result, in this vicious circle, the US economy gradually collapsed, eventually triggering the 2008 financial crisis in the United States.
Therefore, at this stage, the level of China's household debt ratio reached a high of 46.8% is a very need to be vigilant about the problem, this data is still lower than the level of developed countries, but the early signs of the problem have begun to appear, the country has repeatedly emphasized the problem of deleveraging since last year, which is a very prescient judgment, if the household debt rate is allowed to continue to climb, it will inevitably lead to huge risks, so we must strictly prevent the emergence of financial risks.
Therefore, after the house is used to live, not for speculation, the state has accelerated the establishment of multi-subject supply, multi-channel security, rent-purchase and other measures to further resolve potential risks.
For our individual families, we must give up real estate speculative thinking, buy a house when we do our best, to avoid their families into a huge burden, only a reasonable assessment of their income and debt level is a healthy family wealth development path.
Author: Special Researcher of Suning Financial Research Institute, financial columnist, financial commentator.
