White House tools cost thousands of dollars
According to military records released by Time magazine, last month the White House decided to transport a Marine helicopter to the South Lawn to highlight the great glory of American manufacturing, costing up to $24,000.
The green-and-white Sikorsky VH-3D (also known as Marine One when the president rides) was an important exhibit at the White House on July 17 to highlight U.S. construction project activities.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials toured manufactured products from all 50 states.
Exhibits include a Connecticut-built helicopter, a Maine yacht, a Wisconsin fire truck and a Mississippi forklift.
According to the records of the Marine Corps Helicopter First Flying Team (HMX-1), the White House Military Office requested that the helicopter appear on a daily order (FRAGO), that is, only 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn to participate in the "special" event.
The day before the event, Commander HMX-1 said in an email to the superior Marine Corps Deputy Flight Commander that “I just want to confirm that you are aware of this event, which is highly valued.”
This information indicates that the helicopter will arrive at South Lawn at about 7 a.m. on July 17 for the 3 p.m. event, and will leave after the lawn is emptied from 6 p.m. to 9 p.m. on the same day.
The information also said that in the event of a delay in departure from the White House, a second crew would be required for the return flight because of the time limit on duty.
The original crew was on standby at the helicopter side during the event, while security forces personnel were on standby nearby when the aircraft was on the ground.
Time magazine’s records do not say whether a second crew will ultimately be needed.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using government property for political purposes.
HMX-1 had asked if the event violated the Act.
The commander wrote, “One of the questions we asked was whether it was a violation of the Hatch Act and was told there was no violation.”
“Sounds like you’re locked up,” the deputy commander replied.
The White House defines the “Made in America” campaign as an official event and is therefore not governed by the Hatch Act.
But even official events are political.
At the event, the president pushed the Senate’s agenda at the time: health care reform, and touted the regulation of government regulations.
Using Marine One or Air Force One aircraft for propaganda purposes is nothing new.
Presidents have been required to travel on these planes.
However, it is not common to expropriate it for photo purposes only.
Trump received attention in February, when the presidential plane slowly glided in Melbourne, Florida, and finally stopped at the background of his first campaign rally, and his Twitter account was filled with complaints about the former president's use of the presidential plane.
Lindsay Walters, the White House deputy press secretary, said: "The White House is thrilled by this 'Made in America' exhibition, which showcases products from all 50 states that are made from American workers using American materials."
The HMX-1 crew regularly conducts flight training near the Washington area and on the South Lawn, practicing the accurate placement of the president of the United States in the White House.
In early July, during Trump’s G-20 summit in Germany, the HMX-1 practiced 58 landings at the White House.
One official said the U.S.-manufacturing flight was included in this month’s crew training requirements.
The helicopter unit also flew an additional 11 hours of “non-presidential support missions” that day.
The White House said the taxpayers did not bear the cost of any other items at the event.
A Sikorsky spokesman said the company was not involved in arranging the South Lawn helicopter display.
The HMX-1 does not maintain a budget record for the president’s flight, so it is difficult to determine the exact cost of the event.
However, according to the Department of Defense's hourly expenses for fiscal year 2017, the Department of Defense's reimbursement of the VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
The troop records record the aircraft’s time each flight from a base at Marine Corps airfield in Quantico, Virginia, for 30 minutes.
