Therefore, from the perspective of employment, pay and economic prosperity, in the context of Brexit, rising cost of living and a long-term decline in manufacturing, the eastern part of Glasgow urgently needs McVeter to expand its production network.”
A spokesman for Pladis said: “The director of Tollcross received a letter from the Scotland chapter of the General Union of England yesterday and the company will respond immediately as we value ongoing contact with employees and union representatives.
Two months ago, we held regular meetings with employees and representatives of the General Union of England in Tollcross to discuss some issues publicly.
We had discussions with our employees and then, like all other companies operating in a highly competitive and economically uncertain environment, we reviewed the ongoing operating model we applied to businesses and factories to stay competitive.
She added: “In recent years, we have invested more than £5 million at the Tollcross plant, particularly in production lines and operational improvements.
